00:20:30,635 --> 00:20:34,041
Come over here, you'll get
your head kicked in around here.

231
00:20:34,073 --> 00:20:38,309
- You punch-drunk, goofy bastard.
- You ain't no big shot, look at you.

232
00:20:38,310 --> 00:20:42,380
You ain't even got a car
to take that pig home.

233
00:20:44,951 --> 00:20:46,305
You all right?

234
00:20:47,788 --> 00:20:48,820
Yeah.

235
00:20:51,425 --> 00:20:54,343
What are you doing?
Don't get out. It's all right.

236
00:20:57,032 --> 00:21:00,366
No, Little Marie. It ain't all right.

237
00:21:05,008 --> 00:21:06,848
- Yo.
- What?

238
00:21:06,976 --> 00:21:09,028
I'll tell you what. Get inside.

239
00:21:09,113 --> 00:21:12,269
- You get inside. Yeah, you.
- Hey, leave him alone!

240
00:21:12,315 --> 00:21:13,596
- Yo, man!
- See it?

241
00:21:13,717 --> 00:21:16,006
- You see that? You see that?
- Yeah. All right.

242
00:21:16,086 --> 00:21:18,518
- What do you say?
- I'm sorry. I'm sorry!

243
00:21:18,590 --> 00:21:20,323
Get a job!

244
00:21:36,309 --> 00:21:38,362
That guy sends his apologies.

245
00:21:39,145 --> 00:21:40,675
Okay.

246
00:21:57,434 --> 00:22:01,992
Martin. Martin. Yo, Martin!

247
00:22:06,645 --> 00:22:08,627
I see you still got your key.

248
00:22:08,712 --> 00:22:10,694
Yeah, I got a key.
You got time to talk?

249
00:22:11,316 --> 00:22:14,127
I got a lot of time
since your people let me go.

250
00:22:14,186 --> 00:22:16,583
You know I had
nothing to do with that.

251
00:22:16,655 --> 00:22:18,245
Yeah.

252
00:22:19,859 --> 00:22:21,971
Yeah, we moved in
about a year ago.

253
00:22:22,061 --> 00:22:24,493
- Yeah?
- Yeah, I mean, it's only temporary.

254
00:22:24,564 --> 00:22:27,589
- Yeah, I could see that.
- I'm gonna look for an apartment.

255
00:22:27,632 --> 00:22:29,294
Apartments are nice.

256
00:22:29,403 --> 00:22:31,206
Yeah. It is what it is, you know.

257
00:22:31,305 --> 00:22:33,286
Yeah, it is what it is.

258
00:22:33,373 --> 00:22:36,707
This place used to be pretty nice.
There's a lot of history around here.

259
00:22:36,744 --> 00:22:38,333
- Yeah.
- Like down the street...

260
00:22:38,446 --> 00:22:40,107
...is the Cambria Fight Club.

261
00:22:40,216 --> 00:22:42,161
They used to call it
the Bucket of Blood.

262
00:22:42,251 --> 00:22:45,656
I took some massive beatings there.
But it was nice. Good memories.

263
00:22:45,688 --> 00:22:50,969
And I heard these buildings are like,
I don't know, 100, 150 years old.

264
00:22:50,927 --> 00:22:56,208
If I was 150 years old, I'd be falling
apart too. So it's okay, building.

265
00:22:56,166 --> 00:22:57,446
Does that light work?

266
00:22:57,569 --> 00:23:00,001
- No, it's burnt out or something. Yeah.
- Yeah?

267
00:23:02,507 --> 00:23:07,100
Listen, thanks for the ride,
and I'm sorry about those guys.

268
00:23:07,079 --> 00:23:10,793
Some of those guys just got their
brains on backwards and stuff.

269
00:23:10,816 --> 00:23:13,807
- What's he doing out so late?
- Is that your kid?

270
00:23:13,852 --> 00:23:16,071
Yeah. Wish he wouldn't
stay out so late.

271
00:23:16,290 --> 00:23:19,209
- Amazing.
- Yeah, what's that?

272
00:23:19,693 --> 00:23:22,125
Last time I seen you,
you was a kid...

273
00:23:22,196 --> 00:23:24,451
...and now you officially
got one of your own.

274
00:23:24,531 --> 00:23:25,670
It's amazing.

275
00:23:25,799 --> 00:23:30,036
You know, he sort of resembles you.
He's got that big Irish hair.

276
00:23:30,772 --> 00:23:32,089
Yeah, it's the other one.

277
00:23:35,510 --> 00:23:38,013
- Yeah?
- His father was from Jamaica.

278
00:23:38,080 --> 00:23:39,468
Jamaica? European.

279
00:23:42,452 --> 00:23:44,955
Was you on a cruise ship
or something?

280
00:23:45,021 --> 00:23:47,038
- No, not really.
- What's his name?

281
00:23:47,124 --> 00:23:51,918
- Steps. Short for Stevenson.
- Makes sense.

282
00:23:55,266 --> 00:23:58,565
Does he look mad at me, or is it
maybe the angle I'm standing at?

283
00:23:58,603 --> 00:24:01,344
No. He's a good kid.

284
00:24:01,408 --> 00:24:03,947
- You wanna meet him?
- It's getting kind of late.

285
00:24:04,009 --> 00:24:07,758
- I got so many things to do.
- Yeah, yeah, I understand.

286
00:24:08,481 --> 00:24:12,586
Thanks again for the ride
and everything else.

287
00:24:14,455 --> 00:24:16,080
I'll see you.

288
00:24:17,157 --> 00:24:18,652
You too.

289
00:24:18,759 --> 00:24:22,865
Hey, Steps, come on. Let's go.
Say good night to your friend.

290
00:24:22,931 --> 00:24:25,470
What are you doing out
in the cold with no hat on?

291
00:24:25,533 --> 00:24:28,001
- Did you get something to eat?
- Yeah, I already ate.

292
00:24:28,070 --> 00:24:29,731
All right.

293
00:24:29,840 --> 00:24:32,272
- You're late, you know.
- I can take care of myself.

294
00:24:33,009 --> 00:24:35,027
Yo, Little Marie!

295
00:24:36,112 --> 00:24:38,164
Ain't you gonna
introduce me to your kid?

296
00:24:38,249 --> 00:24:40,575
- How you doing, Steps?
- What's up?

297
00:24:40,651 --> 00:24:46,074
Listen, I got this place, this restaurant,
nice little eatery not too far from here.

298
00:24:46,023 --> 00:24:48,076
What's all this junk? Got a tissue.

299
00:24:48,159 --> 00:24:51,980
Sometimes I feel like a kangaroo,
all the stuff in my pocket, you know.

300
00:24:51,998 --> 00:24:54,216
Here you go.
I got a card, there it is.

301
00:24:54,301 --> 00:24:56,448
And if you ever get a chance,
it'd be great...

302
00:24:56,536 --> 00:24:59,490
...if both of youse
come down there and eat.

303
00:24:59,538 --> 00:25:05,626
It'd be great, free. You know.
Anyway, I'll leave it over there... Here.

304
00:25:06,580 --> 00:25:10,259
I'll leave it on the steps. Steps.

305
00:25:13,655 --> 00:25:15,493
See you later.

306
00:25:17,458 --> 00:25:19,404
Come on, let's go.

307
00:25:21,864 --> 00:25:24,261
<i>You've known what's best for you
since you were 10.</i>

308
00:25:24,334 --> 00:25:26,446
Since you walked in here alone.

309
00:25:27,336 --> 00:25:29,911
Got everything money can buy...

310
00:25:29,974 --> 00:25:32,122
...except what it can't.

311
00:25:32,842 --> 00:25:37,007
It's pride. Pride is what got
your ass out of here.

312
00:25:38,349 --> 00:25:40,295
Losing is what brung you back.

313
00:25:41,788 --> 00:25:46,760
But people like you, they need
to be tested. Need a challenge.

314
00:25:46,725 --> 00:25:49,051
That ain't gonna happen.
Ain't nothing out there.

315
00:25:49,295 --> 00:25:52,843
There's always somebody
out there. Always.

316
00:25:53,167 --> 00:25:55,528
When that time comes
and you find something...

317
00:25:55,601 --> 00:25:58,176
...standing in front of you
that ain't running...

318
00:25:58,238 --> 00:26:03,840
...that ain't backing up, hitting on you,
and you're too damn tired to breathe...

319
00:26:03,978 --> 00:26:07,075
You find that situation on you,
that's good.

320
00:26:07,116 --> 00:26:09,749
Because that's baptism under fire.

321
00:26:11,721 --> 00:26:14,533
You get through that,
you find the only kind of respect...

322
00:26:14,590 --> 00:26:16,323
...that matters in this damn world:

323
00:26:16,426 --> 00:26:18,680
Self-respect.

324
00:26:21,131 --> 00:26:24,122
Thanks, Martin. I appreciate that.

325
00:26:24,168 --> 00:26:26,006
Now, what can the champ
do for you?

326
00:26:27,271 --> 00:26:30,047
You can give me
some of that money you got.

327
00:26:31,175 --> 00:26:33,846
- You know, I like you, Martin.
- But not that much.

328
00:26:34,847 --> 00:26:36,924
Exactly.

329
00:26:40,620 --> 00:26:42,945
How about a picture with the kid?
All right?

330
00:26:43,021 --> 00:26:44,481
Sure.

331
00:26:46,359 --> 00:26:49,277
Here, son, hold up your fist.
Makes you look more hazardous.

332
00:26:51,832 --> 00:26:53,148
- There you go.
- Thanks, Rock.

333
00:26:53,268 --> 00:26:55,213
Enjoy your meal.

334
00:26:55,971 --> 00:26:57,631
- He's a nice guy, isn't he?
- Rocky?

335
00:26:57,739 --> 00:26:59,957
- Yeah.
- Spider just went downstairs.

336
00:27:00,041 --> 00:27:02,616
- I don't know if that's all right.
- What's he doing?

337
00:27:02,678 --> 00:27:05,039
I don't know. That's your friend.

338
00:27:11,053 --> 00:27:12,548
Yo, Spider!

339
00:27:12,656 --> 00:27:16,370
- Let me do some dishes. I feel better.
- Come on. You're my guest.

340
00:27:16,393 --> 00:27:18,991
- Let me do something.
- Keep eating. Guests do that.

341
00:27:19,063 --> 00:27:21,602
Don't make me fight you again.
Last time you got lucky.

342
00:27:21,933 --> 00:27:24,081
Lucky? Okay.

343
00:27:24,202 --> 00:27:25,863
Jesus wants me to work.

344
00:27:26,505 --> 00:27:29,080
- Yo, Rocky.
- Yeah?

345
00:27:29,141 --> 00:27:30,280
You've got guests.

346
00:27:32,878 --> 00:27:34,682
Don't get too wet, okay?

347
00:27:36,016 --> 00:27:37,890
Glad Jesus didn't ask you to cook.

348
00:27:44,226 --> 00:27:45,959
You kept the card.

349
00:27:46,060 --> 00:27:47,970
Yeah, I kept the card.

350
00:27:48,064 --> 00:27:50,497
- Why don't you sit down?
- Yeah, sure.

351
00:27:59,976 --> 00:28:04,734
Because, you know what, I walk in
there, I say good morning, I do this:

352
00:28:05,150 --> 00:28:06,467
<i>Tonight, boxing once again.</i>

353
00:28:06,584 --> 00:28:09,467
<i>Two contrasting styles
in almost every way.</i>

354
00:28:09,520 --> 00:28:12,997
Hey, can you turn this up?
Turn this up, please.

355
00:28:13,024 --> 00:28:16,536
<i>Who was the best of all time?
If two athletes from different eras...</i>

356
00:28:16,596 --> 00:28:19,896
<i>... could compete against one another,
who would come out on top?</i>

357
00:28:19,933 --> 00:28:23,896
<i>Given the same rules, using the same
equipment, who was the greatest?</i>

358
00:28:23,903 --> 00:28:25,813
<i>We feed our facts
into the computer.</i>

359
00:28:25,905 --> 00:28:28,408
<i>They weigh in on who they
think will reign supreme...</i>

360
00:28:28,474 --> 00:28:31,737
<i>... while fielding the comments of our
illustrious panel of sportswriters.</i>

361
00:28:37,386 --> 00:28:39,083
Champ!

362
00:28:40,589 --> 00:28:42,119
- Yo, champ!
- Yeah?

363
00:28:42,223 --> 00:28:45,285
Come check out this trash
they're talking about you, man!

364
00:28:45,327 --> 00:28:48,388
- What you talking about?
- Come check this out. Hurry up.

365
00:28:48,565 --> 00:28:51,033
<i>Tonight, the former two-time
heavyweight champion...</i>

366
00:28:51,101 --> 00:28:53,213
<i>... from Philadelphia, Rocky Balboa.</i>

367
00:28:53,303 --> 00:28:55,355
<i>All right, Chuck Johnson,
USA Today?</i>

368
00:28:55,439 --> 00:28:58,321
<i>There's no question that
Rocky Balboa fought tougher fights...</i>

369
00:28:58,375 --> 00:29:00,000
<i>... during a tougher era in boxing.</i>

370
00:29:00,112 --> 00:29:02,021
<i>You look at Mason Dixon
in his career...</i>

371
00:29:02,113 --> 00:29:04,510
<i>... he's basically been
spoon-fed his opponents.</i>

372
00:29:04,582 --> 00:29:06,872
<i>No question in my mind.
Not only does Rocky win...</i>

373
00:29:06,952 --> 00:29:08,305
<i>... but he wins knockout.</i>

374
00:29:10,356 --> 00:29:12,053
Rocky!

375
00:29:13,359 --> 00:29:14,391
Offspring.

376
00:29:15,662 --> 00:29:16,730
<i>Bernard Fernandez?</i>

377
00:29:16,863 --> 00:29:18,703
<i>Dixon is a victim
of his own dominance.</i>

378
00:29:18,798 --> 00:29:21,990
<i>He's never been in
real knockdown-dragout brawls.</i>

379
00:29:22,036 --> 00:29:23,875
<i>He never had to dig down
to rally back.</i>

380
00:29:24,272 --> 00:29:26,253
<i>If he tries to dig down
against Balboa...</i>

381
00:29:26,340 --> 00:29:28,879
<i>... he'll find he doesn't have
a big enough shovel.</i>

382
00:29:28,944 --> 00:29:31,898
<i>I clearly give it to Balboa.</i>

383
00:29:31,981 --> 00:29:35,351
What happened to you?
What happened to you?

384
00:29:35,383 --> 00:29:37,887
<i>Boxing historian
Burt Randolph Sugar.</i>

385
00:29:37,954 --> 00:29:41,289
<i>Dixon has fought cream puffs.
We don't know what he's made of.</i>

386
00:29:41,325 --> 00:29:43,544
<i>But both in their primes,
you gotta factor in...</i>

387
00:29:43,626 --> 00:29:45,608
<i>... Dixon's unbelievable speed...</i>

388
00:29:45,695 --> 00:29:48,437
<i>... his slashing offense.
He cuts Balboa to bits.</i>

389
00:29:48,499 --> 00:29:51,453
<i>No doubt. Dixon wins all the way.</i>

390
00:29:52,638 --> 00:29:57,266
<i>Here's where our subjectivity ends.
Let's see what the computer says.</i>

391
00:29:57,242 --> 00:30:02,214
<i>Dixon unloads on Balboa. Rocky has
no answer. Balboa is eating jabs.</i>

392
00:30:03,049 --> 00:30:04,888
- What time is it?
- Mason time.

393
00:30:05,017 --> 00:30:07,758
- What time is it?
- Mason time.

394
00:30:07,820 --> 00:30:10,075
- What time is it?
- Mason time.

395
00:30:18,367 --> 00:30:23,019
<i>Now Dixon is done. He is reeling.
He is almost out on his feet!</i>

396
00:30:23,005 --> 00:30:25,639
<i>Balboa turning up the heat.
Pounds him across the ring.</i>

397
00:30:25,707 --> 00:30:29,598
<i>Boy, he's bit off more than he
can chew this time. Believe it.</i>

398
00:30:29,611 --> 00:30:33,087
<i>Oh, a murderous right hook!
And Dixon is out on his feet.</i>

399
00:30:33,348 --> 00:30:36,647
<i>He is out cold as he
crumbles to the canvas.</i>

400
00:30:36,686 --> 00:30:41,101
<i>And it is Balboa who has won...</i>

401
00:30:42,027 --> 00:30:44,945
Ladies and gentlemen, Baby Rocky.
Baby Rocky.

402
00:30:51,337 --> 00:30:55,965
I'm glad you liked the food. If you heat
that up, it's pretty good in the morning.

403
00:30:57,044 --> 00:30:58,575
Yeah, thanks, man.

404
00:30:59,047 --> 00:31:02,903
Nice kid. I hope this music ain't giving
you a headache. I like this old stuff.

405
00:31:02,916 --> 00:31:05,170
No, I like it. It's nice.

406
00:31:05,519 --> 00:31:07,631
Well, good. Good.

407
00:31:16,965 --> 00:31:21,380
Yo, you think Steps wants a job?
Make a few bucks on the weekend?

408
00:31:21,371 --> 00:31:25,156
It's good making your own G's. My kid
stashed a few bucks doing that.

409
00:31:25,575 --> 00:31:27,379
Why are you being so nice?

410
00:31:28,546 --> 00:31:30,835
I don't want you to think
nothing's off, you know.

411
00:31:30,916 --> 00:31:34,215
My wife, she's gone, but she ain't.
You know what I mean?

412
00:31:34,251 --> 00:31:36,434
Yeah, well, I wasn't thinking that.
Believe me.

413
00:31:36,521 --> 00:31:39,263
- No? Then what was you thinking?
- No.

414
00:31:39,324 --> 00:31:41,863
That you don't owe us nothing.
What are you doing?

415
00:31:41,928 --> 00:31:43,731
Be patient.

416
00:31:43,829 --> 00:31:45,384
Now...

417
00:31:45,866 --> 00:31:49,971
...I don't owe you nothing,
but why do you gotta...

418
00:31:49,970 --> 00:31:53,755
...owe something to get...?

419
00:31:54,574 --> 00:31:55,855
Bingo.

420
00:32:01,116 --> 00:32:05,637
Why do you gotta owe something
to get something, you know? Really.

421
00:32:08,324 --> 00:32:12,216
I think hanging out with your kid
would be nice. What do you think?

422
00:32:12,229 --> 00:32:14,518
I think that'd be nice.

423
00:32:15,498 --> 00:32:19,082
Good. That's very nice.

424
00:32:19,101 --> 00:32:21,391
I'm glad you come by.

425
00:32:21,772 --> 00:32:25,214
It was nice watching you eat.

426
00:32:26,977 --> 00:32:28,852
Good company.

427
00:32:31,817 --> 00:32:34,487
Yo, Little Marie. Let there be light!

428
00:32:45,432 --> 00:32:47,579
- You like dogs?
- Dogs?

429
00:32:47,668 --> 00:32:52,532
Dogs. This is like a dog pound.
It's where they keep...

430
00:32:52,808 --> 00:32:57,709
...a large variety of dogs. I used to
come here all the time for sightseeing.

431
00:32:57,679 --> 00:33:01,263
But, you know,
you learn a lot talking to dogs.

432
00:33:01,284 --> 00:33:04,891
- Really, you do.
- Yeah, man. So...

433
00:33:04,921 --> 00:33:07,519
Hey, man, how about this one?

434
00:33:09,058 --> 00:33:10,862
He don't look too friendly, my friend.

435
00:33:10,962 --> 00:33:13,774
Man, this is the one.
Hey, boy, how you doing?

436
00:33:13,831 --> 00:33:17,237
Hey, what about this one here?
Come here, boy.

437
00:33:17,267 --> 00:33:18,821
- Who, him?
- Yeah, why not?

438
00:33:18,936 --> 00:33:21,191
Hell, no. That is one ugly dog, man.

439
00:33:21,273 --> 00:33:25,794
I know, but it's kind of a cute ugly.
If you look at it closely, the color...

440
00:33:25,778 --> 00:33:29,777
...it looks like old furniture, like some
kind of pirate-chest thing going on.

441
00:33:29,782 --> 00:33:32,321
Yeah, sure, man.
Hey, so how about a young one?

442
00:33:32,384 --> 00:33:36,028
Steps, forget him. Come over here.
I want you to see something.

443
00:33:36,056 --> 00:33:40,612
Now, you notice what this animal
is doing here? Lying in that position?

444
00:33:40,595 --> 00:33:41,876
He ain't doing nothing.

445
00:33:41,996 --> 00:33:44,844
No, he's doing a lot.
He ain't wasting no energy.

446
00:33:44,899 --> 00:33:46,109
Because he's dead.

447
00:33:52,342 --> 00:33:55,368
He ain't dead. There's a lot of
good mileage left on that animal.

448
00:33:55,410 --> 00:33:59,646
Good food, the addition of a couple
of new friends, bingo, he's back.

449
00:33:59,650 --> 00:34:03,234
- What do you think is a good name?
- It's your dog. You name him.

450
00:34:03,254 --> 00:34:05,960
No. It's, like,
a community animal. Fifty-fifty.

451
00:34:06,024 --> 00:34:08,598
Look, I don't know much
about no dogs.

452
00:34:08,660 --> 00:34:10,356
Well, it ain't that complicated.

453
00:34:10,462 --> 00:34:14,212
You pet him, you feed him,
and nature takes its course.

454
00:34:14,266 --> 00:34:17,222
You know, so...
Don't you wanna name an animal?

455
00:34:17,271 --> 00:34:21,471
Every guy should at one time
try to name an animal something.

456
00:34:21,806 --> 00:34:23,301
I don't know. Fleabag?

457
00:34:24,044 --> 00:34:28,280
It's catchy. It ain't original,
but it's pretty good.

458
00:34:28,282 --> 00:34:30,786
I think you could come up with,
in your young brain...

